<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Finding 1 · Information Disclosure</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/learn.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="learn-page">
    <div class="brand brand-sm" style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
      <span class="brand-mark">⛨</span>
      <span>CySER Workshop · Skyway engagement</span>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-hero">
      <div class="hero-icon">🔎</div>
      <h1>Finding 1 confirmed</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">Day 1 · Information Disclosure in HTML</p>
      <div class="flag-badge"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-grid">
      <div class="learn-card skill-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📚</div>
        <h2>The vulnerability</h2>
        <h3>Secrets in client code</h3>
        <p>Anything sent to the browser is yours forever. HTML comments, hidden elements, <code>data-*</code> attributes, source maps, debug strings. All visible. Base64 hides nothing; <code>atob()</code> reverses it in one line.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card world-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📰</div>
        <h2>Seen in the wild</h2>
        <h3>API keys in JS bundles</h3>
        <p>Companies routinely ship internal API keys, S3 bucket names, admin URLs, and feature flags in compiled JavaScript. Bug-bounty hunters comb minified bundles for <code>data-*</code> attributes, hardcoded tokens, and "TODO" comments daily. And routinely earn payouts.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card career-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🛠️</div>
        <h2>How to fix it</h2>
        <h3>Keep secrets server-side</h3>
        <p>If a string is sensitive, the browser must never see it. Render conditionally based on session state, fetch from an authenticated endpoint, or just don't include it. Treat your source as public.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card key-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔑</div>
        <h2>One-line takeaway</h2>
        <h3>Encoding ≠ secrecy</h3>
        <p>Base64, hex, URL-encoding, ROT13. None of these protect anything from a determined viewer. Encryption with a key the attacker can't read is the only secrecy. Everything else is decoration.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-nav">
      <a href="/" class="nav-btn secondary">← All findings</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %><a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="nav-btn primary">Day <%= nextNum %> →</a><% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
